  faq={[
    {
      q: 'Why should I replace my old silver fillings?',
      a: 'Older amalgam fillings expand and contract with temperature changes, eventually cracking the surrounding tooth. They also contain mercury, which many patients prefer to avoid. Composite fillings bond to the tooth for added strength, look natural, and are metal-free.',
    },
    {
      q: 'How long do tooth-colored fillings last?',
      a: 'With proper oral hygiene and regular checkups, composite fillings last 7–15 years. We monitor all restorations at your checkups and advise you before problems develop.',
    },
    {
      q: 'Does getting a filling hurt?',
      a: 'We use local anesthesia to ensure you feel no pain during the procedure. Some patients experience mild sensitivity to temperature for a few days after, which is normal and resolves on its own.',
    },
    {
      q: 'Can I eat right after a filling?',
      a: 'Composite fillings are hardened immediately with a curing light, so there\'s no waiting period. We recommend avoiding very hot, cold, or hard foods for the first 24 hours as sensitivity settles.',
    },
    {
      q: 'How do I know if I have a cavity?',
      a: 'Many small cavities cause no symptoms — which is why regular X-rays are essential. As cavities grow, you may notice sensitivity or visible discoloration. If you suspect a cavity, call us promptly — smaller cavities require simpler fillings.',
    },
  ]}
